title: Halibut
body:
@taylori 

As you know I've been helping Ian S. with the halibut assessment. Some of his tasks for me were to update/modify r4ss in a way that works for him but should also work for others. I've made all of these changes on the halibut branch:

https://github.com/r4ss/r4ss/commits/halibut

He thinks that a few of these in particular will be of interest to the SS community and that it might be worth trying to get them into the master branch.

Big changes are:
1. Added a new data plot whose circles are proportional (data_plot2.png). Turned on by default, circle sizes and transparencies controlled through top level argument in SS_plots.
2. Redid the empirical weight-at-age plots so they have a legend instead of text (although you can still turn that on; bio4_weightatsize.png)
3. Sex ratio plots for age composition data. Not working for any other data type b/c the halibut assessment doesn't have it, but should be extendable to length easily. See SSPlotSexRatio.R and make_multifig_sexratio.R which were borrowed heavily from SSPlotComps and make_multifig. (sexratio_age-flt10mkt0.png). Admittedly this one is the most "rough" in that it would need further testing.

These work with two halibut models, but these only really differ in the length of the time series, not in any big structural way. I don't have a lot of other models to test them, but I think the new functions should be close.

Up to you which, if any, of these updates to include Ian thinks the sex ratio ones in particular would be useful for @allanhicks.

![bio4_weightatsize](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4804974/12205726/3eae3ef0-b5f1-11e5-949a-2bc5a73aee4e.png)
![data_plot2](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4804974/12205728/3eb5aa00-b5f1-11e5-8b82-4cd83ef27111.png)
![sexratio_age_flt10mkt0](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4804974/12205727/3eb442e6-b5f1-11e5-99ae-295d50eb142d.png)

title: Fix line return due to update of .gitattributes
body:
When we updated the .gitattributes line returns for old files were different for current Windows users. To fix this I followed online instructions (see https://github.com/r4ss/r4ss/issues/81#issuecomment-164904039). 

Basically I fixed them all once and now they should be fine for all users moving forward.

title: Small fixes for CRAN compatibility
body:
I made a number of edits to pass `R CMD check --as-cran` on the current stable version of R and the current version of R-devel.

There are a couple files where I think the Windows/Unix line ending characters made it look like I edited every line. I added a `.gitattributes` file, which I think should fix this in the future. At least it should for new files.

Note that in the development version of R you now have to explicitly import functions from packages that ship with R although you don't have to declare them in the DESCRIPTION file.

title: stackpoly bug fix
body: This fixes a bug in stackpoly that would give an error when you tried to make the plots with solid fill (instead of hashed). The ifelse() functions that were used before would give this error when x.hash was not specified: 'x' is NULL so the result will be NULL. This should fix that problem and allow for making both solid and hashed filled polygons.

title: Update model 'StartTime' in SS_html
body:
In relation to issue #49, @taylori made change to name of model `Run_time`, to `RunTime`, and replaced old `Run_time` with `StartTime`. `SS_html.R` still referred to `Run_time` so returned NULL and left the HTML 'Home' page empty. This simple fix updates the reference for 'Starting time of model:' to the new `replist$StartTime`.

Suggest also that issue #49 can now be closed. :)

title: Addphase
body: Added `newphs` which works with `estimate` to change the phase while also turning the parameter on and off.

title: Jitteriter
body: Updated SS_RunJitter.R to accept a vector of iterations, so you can restart a jitter at an arbitrary number rather than having to run from 1:Njitter only. Also added a return of the likelihood values for each iteration if converged. This is under the assumption that SS pulls the random seed from a clock or something, thus if you run 1:50 on one machine and 51:100 on another machine they will not be using the same par values. Something that might need to be checked.
